1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 Nc6 8. Qd2
O-O 9. O-O-O d5 10. Qe1 e5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. exd5 Nxd5 ({Not} 12... cxd5 $2 {
when} 13. Bg5 {is good for White}) 13. Bc4 Be6 14. Ne4 ({The text was often
used by Kramnik, but more popular of late has been} 14. Kb1) 14... Qc7 15. Bc5
Rfd8 16. Qh4 h6 17. g4 Rab8 {I wanted to keep the queens on the board} ({
I remember getting crushed after} 17... f5 18. gxf5 gxf5 19. Rhg1 $1 fxe4 20.
Qxh6 Qf7 21. Rxg7+ Qxg7 22. Rg1 {in Langer-Findlay, Calgary International 2016,
when White's attack is irresistable}) ({The most popular move in my database is
} 17... Nf4 {but after} 18. Bxe6 Nxe6 19. Qe7 Qa5 20. Rxd8+ Rxd8 21. Qxa7 Qxa7
22. Bxa7 Ra8 23. Be3 Rxa2 24. Kb1 {White has a slight advantage in the endgame}
) ({Also possible is} 17... Rd7 {which I rejected because it leaves my rook
under attack after} 18. g5 h5 19. Nf6+ Nxf6 20. Bxe6) 18. g5 h5 19. Nf6+ $2 {
Now Black takes over the initiative. With White's hanging pieces and weak back
rank, a quiet alternative would have been better} (19. Qf2) (19. Rhe1) 19...
Nxf6 20. gxf6 Bh6+ 21. Kb1 Rxd1+ {Here I saw a forcing line where Black gets
control of the d/file. This I could not resist!} ({The engines like the
thematic} 21... Rd5 $1 {where Black gives an exchange in order to repair his
pawn structure and keep the bishop pair}) 22. Rxd1 Rd8 23. Rg1 Bxc4 $6 ({
Instead of giving White's queen the ideal square c4, from which she is nearly
impossible to dislodge, a better option is} 23... Bf5) 24. Qxc4 Rd5 25. a3 ({
Slightly better might be} 25. a4 {when control of b5 with an extra tempo might
be important in some endings}) 25... Qd7 $6 ({Black should instead remove the
pesky kingside intruder with} 25... Qd8 26. Bxa7 Qxf6 $15) 26. Ka2 Kh7 27. Be7
Kg8 {I did not have a clear plan, but was hoping to improve my position later
with something like ...Qe6} 28. Qe4 Kh7 29. Qc4 Be3 {Unsure of how to win
Black is just marking time. Another logical post for the bishop is on f4, but
White seems to have a grip on the position at this point} 30. Re1 Bf4 31. Re2
Qb7 32. Qb3 $2 {This is exactly what I wanted. White gives up his bind and
allows the opponent to win an endgame with opposite majorities} ({Better is}
32. a4 {to block access to b5 for Black's queen}) 32... Qxb3+ 33. Kxb3 g5 34.
Rg2 Kg6 35. Kc4 Kf5 $2 {I was fixated on the idea that Black needs to leave
the rook on d5 to stop all counterplay} ({Better is} 35... h4 {when there is
no reason to fear} 36. h3 {since after} Rd1 37. Kc5 Rf1 $19 {White has fatal
kingside weaknesses}) 36. b4 e4 $2 ({Once again the plan beginning with} 36...
h4 {is stronger}) 37. fxe4+ Kxe4 38. Bc5 a6 39. Re2+ Kf5 40. Bd4 g4 41. Re7 Kg6
42. Re2 h4 43. Kd3 Kf5 44. c4 Rd8 45. a4 g3 $6 ({The engine finds} 45... Bxh2
$1 46. Rxh2 g3 47. Rxh4 Rxd4+ {and the g/pawn is unstoppable}) 46. hxg3 hxg3
47. Kc3 $1 {Black was threatening 47...g2 48.Rxg2 Be5 winning the bishop} Bg5
$1 {Now Black transposes into a winning rook and pawn ending} 48. b5 cxb5 49.
axb5 axb5 50. cxb5 Bxf6 51. Bxf6 Kxf6 52. Rg2 Rg8 53. Kd4 Kf5 54. Ke3 Kg4 55.
b6 Re8+ 56. Kd3 Kf3 57. Rc2 Rd8+ 58. Kc4 g2 59. Rc3+ Kf4 0-1

