1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. h3 $1 {Avoiding my
opponent's preparation in the main lines, such as} (6. Bg5) (6. Be2) 6... e5 7.
Nb3 ({Previously the knight would retreat with} 7. Nde2 {en route to g3. I saw
Shabalov win a nice game in Edmonton earlier this year with the text move, and
thought to emulate him if possible}) 7... Be7 8. g4 h6 9. Bg2 Be6 10. f4 exf4 {
Black allows his opponent to develop the bishop with tempo, but 11.f5 may have
been a threat} ({Slightly better might have been} 10... O-O {or}) (10... Nc6 {
but we are on new theoretical ground}) 11. Bxf4 Nc6 12. Qe2 {In the above
mentioned Shabalov game, Alex kept his bishop on f1, played O-O-O and was able
to meet ...Ne5 with Nd4 to stop ...Nc4. That might have been a better setup
for White here as well} Ne5 ({The engine prefers routing the other knight to
e5 starting with} 12... Nd7) 13. O-O-O Nfxg4 $6 {The problem with Black's
conception is not the material balance, but the fact that his opponent has
access to the important central squares d5 and f5 for his knights, which soon
starts a strong counter-attack} 14. hxg4 Bxg4 15. Qd2 Bxd1 16. Rxd1 O-O $6 {
Now White can focus his pieces on the attack} ({A better strategy for Black is
to try for a simplified position by offering to trade bishops with} 16... Bg5 {
when I intended to answer with} 17. Nd5) 17. Kb1 g5 $2 {Black weakens the
light squares around his king, giving the opposing knights access to d5 and f5,
while the light squared bishop becomes active on either the h3-c8 or a2-g8
diagonal. Black's defense is not a pleasant one} 18. Bxe5 dxe5 19. Qe2 Qc8 20.
Nd5 Bd8 21. Qh5 Kg7 $2 (21... Qc6 $142 22. Rh1 Qg6 $16) 22. Ne3 Rh8 23. Bh3 Qc6
24. Rd7 $2 (24. Rd6 $142 Qxe4 25. Nf5+ Kf8 26. Rxh6 Rg8 27. Rh7 Qh1+ 28. Nc1
Qd5 29. Qh6+ Ke8 30. Nd6+ $18) 24... Qg6 25. Nf5+ Kg8 26. Qd1 $2 (26. Rxd8+
Rxd8 27. Ne7+ $18) 26... Qb6 27. Qd5 Rh7 28. a4 Bf6 29. Rd6 Qg1+ 30. Ka2 Bg7
31. Ne7+ {Mate follows} 1-0

